{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing: full-series global thresholds (p50, p95) were computed and stored in agg_metric / agg_trace / agg_log, and the original data filtered to the incident window (metric_window, trace_window, log_window). The next step is anomaly detection: identify component-KPI / component-trace / component-log groups that exceed their global thresholds inside the incident window so we can narrow candidate faulty components and time ranges. We should produce compact aggregates per group: count of anomaly points, earliest anomaly timestamp, max value observed in-window, the group's global p95 threshold, and a severity indicator (how far the max exceeds p95). This will let us prioritize groups for fault-identification and subsequent trace/log correlation.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using kernel variables agg_metric, metric_window, agg_trace, trace_window, agg_log, and log_window: \n1) Metric anomaly scan: For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present in agg_metric, get its global p95 (from agg_metric) and scan metric_window for matching (cmdb_id, kpi_name) rows. Find rows where value >= p95. For each group produce a single-row summary with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count (number of rows in-window with value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_ts (min timestamp among those rows), latest_anomaly_ts (max timestamp among those rows), max_value_in_window (max value for that group within the window), p95_threshold, severity_ratio (if p95_threshold>0 then max_value_in_window / p95_threshold else set severity_ratio = max_value_in_window). Keep groups with anomaly_count>0. Return top 20 groups sorted by anomaly_count desc then severity_ratio desc. Store full anomalies table in kernel variable metric_anoms.\n2) Trace anomaly scan: For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in agg_trace, get p95 and scan trace_window to find rows where value >= p95. For each group produce: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, p95_threshold, severity_ratio (same formula). Keep groups with anomaly_count>0. Return top 20 groups sorted by anomaly_count desc then severity_ratio desc. Store full table in trace_anoms.\n3) Log anomaly scan: For each (cmdb_id, log_name) in agg_log, get p95 and scan log_window for rows where value >= p95. For each group produce: cmdb_id, log_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, p95_threshold, severity_ratio (same formula). Keep groups with anomaly_count>0. Return top 20 groups sorted by anomaly_count desc then severity_ratio desc. Store full table in log_anoms.\n4) Limit all returned rows to at most 20 rows per table and return only the columns specified above. If any group's p95_threshold equals NaN or missing, skip that group and report its name in a short list (up to 20) in the output. Do not print raw long series; only the compact anomaly summary tables."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed threshold calculation and anomaly detection. Metric anomalies show many groups at-or-above their p95 through the whole incident window (many anomaly_count=31), but most of those only equal the p95 (severity_ratio≈1.0) and therefore may be false positives or normal high-percentile behavior. Trace anomalies highlight specific flows with substantially elevated latency (severity_ratio up to ~2.16) involving MG01/MG02 and some Tomcat nodes. Log anomalies show GC pause spikes on Tomcat01/03/04 (severity ~1.1–1.2) and no increase in error_count. According to the diagnosis rules, we must now (1) perform fault identification by finding consecutive anomalous sub-series and filtering out isolated/noise spikes and weak breaches, and (2) use traces and logs to localize the root cause among candidate components (prefer downstream faulty service in traces). Key observation so far: the strongest anomalies by severity are in traces for MG01/MG02-related paths (severity >1.9) and GC pause spikes on Tomcat nodes are modest (≈10–20%). Many metric groups merely meet p95 (severity≈1.0) and should be deprioritized unless they form sustained, strongly-breaching faults. Next we must produce compact candidate summaries per component from metrics, traces, and logs so we can pick which component and exact time to inspect further.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Produce compact fault-candidate summaries (bounded outputs) using metric_anoms, trace_anoms, and log_anoms already in the kernel:\n1) Metric-driven component summary: Group metric_anoms by cmdb_id and compute for each component: num_anom_groups (count of distinct kpi_name with anomaly_count>0), num_high_sev_groups (count of groups with severity_ratio >= 1.3), max_severity_ratio (max severity_ratio among its groups), earliest_anomaly_ts (min earliest_anomaly_ts among its groups). Store as component_metric_summary and return top 20 rows sorted by num_anom_groups desc then max_severity_ratio desc. Columns: cmdb_id, num_anom_groups, num_high_sev_groups, max_severity_ratio, earliest_anomaly_ts.\n2) Trace-driven high-severity anomalies: From trace_anoms, keep only rows where cmdb_id is one of the allowed root-cause components [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02] and severity_ratio >= 1.3. Store as trace_candidate_anoms and return all matching rows (limit to top 20) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, p95_threshold, severity_ratio. Sort by severity_ratio desc then anomaly_count desc.\n3) Log-driven anomalies of interest: From log_anoms, return rows where cmdb_id is in the allowed list and severity_ratio >= 1.05 (to catch GC spikes and notable row_count increases). Store as log_candidate_anoms and return up to 20 rows with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, p95_threshold, severity_ratio sorted by severity_ratio desc then anomaly_count desc.\nLimit each returned table to at most 20 rows. Keep full result tables in kernel variables component_metric_summary, trace_candidate_anoms, log_candidate_anoms for next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing, global-threshold calculation, anomaly detection, and an initial fault-candidate ranking. What has been done: agg_metric/agg_trace/agg_log were computed (global p50/p95); data were filtered to the incident window; anomalies were detected (points >= group p95) and summarized as metric_anoms, trace_anoms, log_anoms; component-level summaries were produced (component_metric_summary), and high-severity trace and log candidates were extracted (trace_candidate_anoms, log_candidate_anoms). What can be derived so far: trace anomalies with the largest severity ratios point to MG01 and MG02 (flows from dockerA*/dockerB* to MG nodes) with severity up to ~2.16, and their anomaly timestamps cluster around 1615012680–1615013040. Tomcat nodes show modest GC pause spikes (severity ~1.1–1.2) and Mysql nodes show many metric anomalies (large number of KPI groups and some high severity groups) but many metric groups only meet p95 without big breach. According to the diagnosis rules, traces should be used to localize the root cause among multiple faulty services; the strongest evidence currently is the high-severity trace spikes involving MG01/MG02. Next we must inspect the raw trace rows (within the incident window) for MG01 and MG02 high-severity trace names to determine the exact earliest occurrence timestamps and whether these are consecutive faults (not isolated). This will let us identify the earliest fault point (root cause occurrence time) and whether MG01 or MG02 is the root cause service. We should also later cross-check MG node resource metrics and downstream Tomcat GC spikes, but first we must precisely identify the first anomalous trace samples for MG01/MG02.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace_window, return up to 20 rows where cmdb_id is 'MG01' or 'MG02' AND trace_name contains any of the substrings 'dockerA', 'dockerB', or 'Tomcat'. For each matching row return columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value. Sort results by timestamp ascending. Also return a compact per-(cmdb_id, trace_name) summary (limit 20 rows) containing: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count_in_window (count of rows in the window for that trace_name), earliest_ts_in_window (min timestamp), latest_ts_in_window (max timestamp), max_value_in_window. Keep outputs bounded to at most 20 rows each." }

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through preprocessing, global-threshold calculation, anomaly detection, and candidate ranking. What has been done: agg tables (p50/p95) were computed; data were filtered to the incident window; anomalies were detected (points >= p95) and summarized into metric_anoms, trace_anoms, log_anoms; component-level summaries (component_metric_summary) show Mysql01/02, Tomcat nodes, Redis, MG01/MG02 and IG01/IG02 with many anomalous KPI groups. Trace-driven candidates with the highest severity point to MG01 and MG02 (flows involving dockerA*/dockerB* → MG*) with severity ratios up to ~2.16 and earliest anomaly timestamps around 1615012800. Log-driven anomalies show modest GC pause spikes on Tomcat nodes (severity ~1.1–1.2) with some occurrences earlier (~1615012380). According to the diagnosis rules, traces should be used to localize the root cause among same-level faulty components, and faults with much larger deviations (>>50%) should be preferred when comparing across levels. Current evidence: MG01/MG02 trace anomalies have the largest severity ratios, suggesting MG nodes are the most likely root cause level. To finalize root cause component and exact occurrence time, we must determine the earliest anomalous trace event among high-severity trace anomalies and confirm supporting high-severity resource metrics on that MG node (to justify the reason). Therefore we need compact evidence: the earliest high-severity trace anomaly row(s) and the high-severity metric anomalies for MG01/MG02 (severity >= 1.3) with their earliest timestamps so we can pick the root cause component and occurrence timestamp and state the reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "1) From trace_candidate_anoms (the trace anomalies already filtered for allowed components and severity >=1.3), find the row(s) with the minimum earliest_anomaly_ts (earliest occurrence). Return up to 5 rows (if ties) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, p95_threshold, severity_ratio. Sort by earliest_anomaly_ts ascending.

2) From metric_anoms, return all rows where cmdb_id is 'MG01' or 'MG02' AND severity_ratio >= 1.3 and anomaly_count > 0. Return up to 20 rows sorted by severity_ratio desc then anomaly_count desc. Columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, p95_threshold, severity_ratio.

Keep outputs compact (limit rows as specified) and store the returned tables in kernel variables earliest_trace_anoms and mg_metric_highsev for later steps." }

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through the full workflow: preprocessing (agg tables with global p50/p95), anomaly detection (metric_anoms, trace_anoms, log_anoms), and initial fault identification / candidate ranking. What has been done: component-level summaries show Mysql nodes, Tomcat nodes, Redis, MG01/MG02 and IG01/IG02 with many anomalous KPI groups. Trace anomalies with the largest severity implicate MG01 and MG02 (flows from dockerA*/dockerB* → MG*), with severity up to ~2.16 clustered around timestamps ~1615012680–1615013040. Log anomalies show GC pause spikes on Tomcat nodes (moderate severity ~1.1–1.2). Recent focused checks found: the earliest high-severity candidate trace row was MG02 trace.from_dockerA1.row_count with earliest timestamp 1615012200 (severity ~1.31, anomaly_count=2), while MG01/MG02 duration_p95 anomalies of higher severity occurred later (~1615012800). MG01 also shows a late TCP FIN-WAIT spike at 1615013880 (severity ~6.7). What can be derived: MG nodes (MG01/MG02) are the strongest suspects by trace severity, but we must distinguish sustained faults from isolated spikes. The next necessary step is to verify whether these high-severity trace anomalies on MG01/MG02 are consecutive faults (multi-minute runs) or isolated points. This will let us pick the root cause component and the earliest fault occurrence time consistent with a real fault rather than a transient spike.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For all trace groups in trace_anoms where cmdb_id is 'MG01' or 'MG02' and p95_threshold is present: scan trace_window rows for that (cmdb_id, trace_name) and find all timestamps where value >= that group's p95_threshold. For each group return a compact summary (limit to top 20 groups) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95_threshold, max_value_in_window, list_of_anomaly_timestamps (sorted asc, limit to first 50 timestamps if many), earliest_anomaly_ts, total_anomaly_count, longest_consecutive_run_length (where consecutive means successive timestamps differ by <= 60 seconds), longest_run_start_ts, longest_run_end_ts. Sort the returned groups by longest_consecutive_run_length desc then by max_value_in_window desc. Store the full result in kernel variable trace_fault_segments. Keep the output bounded to at most 20 rows." }

